<h4>Research interests</h4>
<p>
<i>American Politics:</i> U.S. Supreme Court, Congressional Cosponsorship, Roll-Call Voting, Official Secrecy.
<div id="smalltext"> 
<i>Political Methodology:</i> Social Network Analysis, Event History Modeling, Robust Estimation, Machine Learning.</div>
</p>



<h4>Research Agenda</h4>
<p>
As an aspiring political methodologist, I have designed a research agenda in which I aim to advance the techniques political scientists use to understand the dynamics of interdependent political events. The substantive applications in my work are primarily to intra-institutional dynamics in the U.S - including U.S. Supreme Court Voting, Congressional Roll-Call Voting, and Congressional Cosponsorship. I have accumulated a secondary line of work on network phenomena in international relations. 
</p>
<p>
An overarching theme in my work is a theoretical approach to the interdependence of outcomes across and within political institutions. In many fields of applied statistics, non-independence of observations in a study is treated as a nuisance introduced by sub-optimal research design. As a result, the methods developed to deal with dependent data tend to engage the interdendence to the minimum degree necessary to consistently estimate whatever marginal characteristics are of interest. In my dissertation, and related work, I (1) make the case that a full theoretical engagement with the form of dependence is essential to a comprehensive understanding of political phenomena, (2) develop algorithms that can be used to identify interesting types of interdependence in common discrete choice datasets, (3) propose models that can be used to estimate effects on both the marginal behavior of political actors and the dependence between them, and (4) demonstrate through applications how theoretical considerations of interdependence can improve the predictive performance of empirical models. 
</p>


</td>


