</td>
<td width="400">
<p><b>The Self-Correcting U.S. Supreme Court</b></p>
<p>Many of the conservative U.S. Supreme Court decisions of the past three decades have been interpreted as negative responses to the liberal doctrine of the Warren Court. In these accounts  it is hypothesized that the Court has acted to counter the ideological extremity of its past, thus desirably updating the extant understanding of the law. The idea that the Court is an explicitly self-correcting institution has never been considered in the context of quantitative scholarship on Court dynamics. The Court operates with the objective of exercising optimal ideological influence on subsequent users of its doctrine. Moreover, those users respond to relevant bodies of legal policy and not <i>typically</i> single cases in isolation. The intersection of these facts produces a strong incentive for the Court to correct past ideological extremes. Empirical results show that the Court acts in a manner consistent with a self-correcting institution.
</p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr>

<tr>
