</td>
<td width="400">
<p><b>Model Improvement through Multivariate Error Analysis</b></p>
<p>
The systematic analysis of residuals from regression models has long been used to monitor many aspects of model fit. In models where the dependent variable consists of repeated collective choices, a common configuration in political science, a particularly informative residual concept is the <i>joint prediction error </i> (JPE). A JPE is a collective outcome that is poorly predicted by a discrete choice model. Analysis of these joint residuals (1) exposes dependence patterns that are inconsistent with the multivariate structure of the specified model, and (2) the intersection of the component parts in a JPE can indicate important explanatory variables that are missing. I derive an algorithm that finds JPEs in a discrete-choice dataset. Analysis of prediction errors is shown to improve empirical models from two published works, one on U.S. Supreme Court voting in the <i>American Political Science Review</i>, and another on the fulfillment of international defense alliances in the <i>American Journal of Political Science</i>.
</p>
</td>
</tr>

